40:55.586 --> 40:57.822 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I wanted to talk about walking
through it.

40:57.855 --> 41:00.358 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I really wanted to get this park
on the page.

41:00.391 --> 41:04.996 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: The park is in
the Brooklyn
neighborhood of Bushwick, where
author Jacqueline

41:05.029 --> 41:07.932 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Woodson came of age in the
1970s.

41:07.965 --> 41:13.137 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Her new novel, set in that time
and place,
is about four teenage friends,
as Woodson

41:13.171 --> 41:18.910 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
writes, growing up girl in the
city, with
big aspirations, but also
suffering terrible

41:18.943 --> 41:21.112 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
losses along the way.

41:21.145 --> 41:22.914 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's called "Another Brooklyn."

41:22.947 --> 41:25.516 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JACQUELINE WOODSON: I knew that
it was going
to be an story about friendship
and the way

41:25.550 --> 41:29.620 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
people come together and
eventually come apart.

41:29.654 --> 41:31.823 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
So, I just went in.

41:31.856 --> 41:38.830 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, of course, having grown up
girl in Brooklyn
myself, it was -- it was -- I
had some information

41:38.863 --> 41:40.565 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that I needed to tell this
story.

41:40.598 --> 41:43.134 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And you wanted to
tell this
because?

41:43.167 --> 41:50.041 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JACQUELINE WOODSON: I don't
think it's a story
that's really been told in that
way that we

41:50.074 --> 41:56.681 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
talk intimately about the
complexity of what
it means to grow up, not only
girl, but to

41:56.714 --> 42:03.020 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
grow up a girl of color, and
grow up specifically
an African-American girl, or a
Caribbean-American

42:03.054 --> 42:05.089 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
girl, in the city.

42:05.123 --> 42:10.428 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I had the main character of
Bushwick, which
is a character I knew well
because I grew

42:10.461 --> 42:11.996 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
up there, but I wanted...

42:12.029 --> 42:13.798 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: You mean the
place as a character?

42:13.831 --> 42:14.899 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JACQUELINE WOODSON: Yes, the
place.

42:14.932 --> 42:16.667 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So, you felt that
from the
beginning?

42:16.701 --> 42:18.202 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JACQUELINE WOODSON: Yes, yes, I
knew that
Bushwick was going to be the
main character,

42:18.236 --> 42:22.373 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that everything was going to
revolve in this
neighborhood.

42:22.407 --> 42:27.011 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: The Bushwick of
the 1970s that
Woodson describes had more than
its share

42:27.044 --> 42:31.149 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
of problems and dangers,
especially for young
girls.

42:31.182 --> 42:32.350 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Drugs were everywhere.

42:32.383 --> 42:34.519 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
White flight was well under way.

42:34.552 --> 42:39.724 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But she also recalls a vibrant
place, with
young people, like her
characters, who aspired

42:39.757 --> 42:41.559 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to and achieved great things.

42:41.592 --> 42:46.364 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JACQUELINE WOODSON: It was very
much alive,
and I wanted to capture that,
especially given

42:46.397 --> 42:50.334 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
how people think of Bushwick as
this place
that's newly discovered.

42:50.368 --> 42:56.107 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And every time I hear that, I'm
just like,
no, there were people here
before then.

42:56.140 --> 42:58.643 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Do you fear that
that history
has been lost?

42:58.676 --> 43:00.445 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Is that part of what is going on
here?

43:00.478 --> 43:02.413 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JACQUELINE WOODSON: Yes, I think
it can get
lost.

43:02.447 --> 43:05.550 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But I think writers are the
history keepers,
right?

43:05.583 --> 43:10.488 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We're the ones who are bearing
witness to
what's going on in the world.

43:10.521 --> 43:15.393 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I feel like it's our job to
put that down
on paper, and put it out into
the world, so

43:15.426 --> 43:17.261 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
that it can be remembered.

43:17.295 --> 43:21.199 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Woodson told her
own story
of growing up in South Carolina
and then Brooklyn

43:21.232 --> 43:27.004 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in her 2014 free verse memoir
"Brown Girl
Dreaming," where she describes
how she dreamed

43:27.038 --> 43:29.307 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of being a writer at the age of
7.

43:29.340 --> 43:33.177 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Why a writer?

43:33.211 --> 43:36.781 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JACQUELINE WOODSON: When I was a
kid, I got
in trouble for lying a lot, and
I had a teacher

43:36.814 --> 43:40.418 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
say, instead of lying, write it
down, because
if you write it down, it's not a
lie anymore;

43:40.451 --> 43:41.385 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
it's fiction.

43:41.419 --> 43:42.587 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
So I was, like, wait.

43:42.620 --> 43:43.754 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Ah, that's your
definition
of fiction.

43:43.788 --> 43:44.755 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

43:44.789 --> 43:45.756 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JACQUELINE WOODSON: Yes.

43:45.790 --> 43:46.757 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's legitimized.

43:46.791 --> 43:48.159 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I was like, wait, there's a way
out of this.

43:48.192 --> 43:51.529 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, also, I just loved the
physical act of
writing.

43:51.562 --> 43:55.900 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And when I learned to write my
name for the
first time, there was such a
power to realizing

43:55.933 --> 43:59.337 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that you put letters together,
and they make
words, and you put words
together, and they

43:59.370 --> 44:01.639 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
make sentences, and sentences
make paragraphs.

44:01.672 --> 44:08.212 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that was magic to me, that
all you needed
was this pencil and a notebook,
and you were

44:08.246 --> 44:09.514 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
on your way.

44:09.547 --> 44:12.984 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: On her way to a
life of writing
and many honors.

44:13.017 --> 44:16.420 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Woodson is author of more than
30 books for
children and young adults.

44:16.454 --> 44:20.358 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Her memoir won the National Book
Award for
Young People's Literature.

44:20.391 --> 44:24.462 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The new novel is her first for
adults in 20
years.

44:24.495 --> 44:27.665 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Woodson still lives in Brooklyn
in a different
neighborhood.

44:27.698 --> 44:31.836 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And when we returned with her to
Bushwick,
she kept running into old
friends, this one

44:31.869 --> 44:34.472 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
